{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647061"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:39:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:39:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18223"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18223"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77477"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10937"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25422"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77477"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOsteoporosis is a condition characterised by decreased bone density and increased fragility, leading to a higher risk of fractures. It is particularly prevalent in postmenopausal women and the elderly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common type of fracture associated with osteoporosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pelvic fracture","Vertebral compression fracture","Humeral head fracture","Distal radius fracture","Femoral neck fracture"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertebral compression fractures\u003C/strong\u003E occur when the vertebrae in the spine are compressed due to weakened bone structure, often resulting in height loss and kyphosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral neck fracture\u003C/strong\u003E - While common in osteoporosis especially in the elderly, it is not as frequent as vertebral fractures\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistal radius fracture\u003C/strong\u003E - Also known as a Colles\u0027 fracture, it is common but less so than vertebral fractures\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHumeral head fracture\u003C/strong\u003E - Less common in osteoporosis compared to vertebral and femoral neck fractures\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic fracture\u003C/strong\u003E - These are less common and usually occur with significant trauma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOsteoporotic fractures can occur with minimal trauma, particularly in weight-bearing bones like the vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteoporosis commonly leads to fractures due to decreased bone density and strength.","Vertebral compression fractures are the most common type of fractures associated with osteoporosis.","Osteoporotic fractures can occur with minimal trauma, particularly in weight-bearing bones."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04151206. PMID: 18988698; PMCID: PMC3152283","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. 2024 Apr 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725884","Porter JL, Varacallo M. Osteoporosis. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722930.","LeBoff MS, Greenspan SL, Insogna KL, Lewiecki EM, Saag KG, Singer AJ, Siris ES. The clinician\u0027s guide to prevention and treatment of osteoporosis. Osteoporos Int. 2022 Oct;33(10):2049-2102. doi: 10.1007/s00198-021-05900-y. Epub 2022 Apr 28. Erratum in: Osteoporos Int. 2022 Oct;33(10):2243. doi: 10.1007/s00198-022-06479-8. PMID: 35478046; PMCID: PMC9546973."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18223"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62989"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T08:59:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T09:00:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10937"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77477"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i